## What the test claims

`tests/conformance_prime_migrate.rs::prime_migrate_on_already_xdg_is_a_noop` (lines 53-67):

```rust
#[test]
fn prime_migrate_on_already_xdg_is_a_noop() {
    let home = tmp();
    let (_remote, clone, _url) = legacy_clone(home.path(), "dev/proj");
    bl_xdg(&clone, home.path()).arg("migrate").assert().success();
    let head_before = git(&clone, &["rev-parse", "HEAD"]).trim().to_string();

    let out = bl_xdg(&clone, home.path())
        .args(["prime", "--migrate"])
        .output()
        .unwrap();
    assert!(out.status.success(), "re-run failed: {}", String::from_utf8_lossy(&out.stderr));

    let head_after = git(&clone, &["rev-parse", "HEAD"]).trim().to_string();
    assert_eq!(head_before, head_after, "prime --migrate must add no commit on an XDG clone");
}
```

## What the SPEC requires

`docs/SPEC-clone-layout.md` line 414:

> `bl migrate` is idempotent: re-running on an already-migrated clone is a no-op (it observes that no `.balls/` exists at the clone root, no `<origin-key>` subtree exists under `~/.local/state/balls/`, and nothing on `main` needs to be removed).

And line 484 (§14.21):

> **Migration is one-shot — pre-XDG path.** Running `bl migrate` on a pre-XDG clone produces (a) the documented nested XDG tree, (b) one commit on `main` removing the in-repo `.balls/` and `.gitignore` entries, and (c) no further state in the clone's working tree. Re-running `bl migrate` is a no-op.

So the contract has three surfaces: no commit on main, no new XDG subtree (idempotent), no working-tree changes.

## The gap

The test name claims "noop" but the assertion only covers surface (1): `HEAD` on main is unchanged. It does not snapshot the XDG state branch tip, the per-clone subtree under `~/.local/state/balls/`, or the working tree. Today this catches the only mutating surface `bl prime --migrate` exposes (the migrate verb's main-branch commit), because the impl gates on `is_legacy(&store.root)` (`src/commands/sync.rs:143`) and on an XDG clone simply skips the migrate body. But if a future change made `prime --migrate` mutate state outside `main` — touching the state branch, materializing scratch dirs, rewriting `clone.json` — the test would silently keep passing while the name continued to promise more than it delivers.

## Not the bl-fc1d class

bl-fc1d hunted fixtures rigged to a buggy impl's mental model. This one is different: the fixture is faithful (real `bl migrate` produces real XDG state) and the assertion isn't tautological — it actually tests a real contract. The narrowness is just that the test name overpromises relative to what the SPEC defines as "no-op."

## Fix shape

Either:

- (a) **Tighten the assertion** to match the name: snapshot HEAD on main + state-branch tip + `XdgBases` per-clone subtree hash before and after; assert all unchanged. Catches future mutations across the full no-op surface.
- (b) **Tighten the name** to match the assertion: rename to `prime_migrate_on_already_xdg_adds_no_main_commit` and leave the assertion alone. Cheaper, less protective.

Recommended: (a). The state-branch-tip and per-clone-subtree snapshots already exist as helpers in other XDG conformance tests; bolting them on costs ~10 lines.

## Audit trail

Surfaced by bl-fc1d audit, flagged as a test-name-vs-assertion overpromise that did not meet the bar for the audit's class of bug. Filed for clarity per follow-up request 2026-05-25.
